Preheat your oven to 200°C. Peel and finely chop the @garlic clove{1} and add a
sprinkle of @salt{}. Push the flat of your #knife{} on top and drag firmly across
the garlic. Keep doing this until the garlic becomes a paste.

Cut the @vine tomatoes{1} into ½cm slices. Chop the @sweet potato{1%small} (no need
to peel) into wedges about the size of your index finger. Pop the wedges on a
#baking tray{} and toss in a glug of @olive oil{} with a pinch of @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Cook on the top shelf of your oven for around ~{20-25%minutes}
(until crispy at the edges).

Add the @Cajun spice mix{1} with a splash of @olive oil{} to a #mixing bowl{} and
stir together. Cut the @halloumi{1} cheese into slices just under 1cm thick. Rub
the Cajun spice infused oil over the halloumi.

Put the @sour cream{1/2%cup} in a #small bowl{} and combine with a tiny bit of
your garlic paste. Add a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Taste and add more
garlic paste if you think it needs it.

When the sweet potato wedges are 5 mins away from cooked, heat a #frying pan{}
on medium-high heat. When the pan is hot, gently lay in the halloumi slices and
cook for ~{2%minutes} on each side, turning once. Remove the wedges from your
oven.

Cut the @brioche buns{2} in half and put them on the top shelf of your oven for
~{2%minutes} (no more!) to crisp them up. Meanwhile, remove the root from the
@baby gem lettuce{1} and finely slice (ie shred) widthways. Lay the halloumi on
the bottom half of the bun. Top with the lettuce, tomato slices and a dollop of
garlic sour cream. Finish with the top half of the bun. Serve your burgers with
some sweet potato wedges on the side. Enjoy!

> The secret's in the sauce: pushing garlic to a paste spreads flavour evenly in
> the garlic sour cream, making this recipe truly special.